If any 11th or 12th graders are interested in the CNA (certified nusing assistant) program, please text me (Hendi :) ) at 218 750-2980

Mesabi Range College works with us to provide CNA classes (their teacher, Kathy, is great!) and the next session is starting when high school does or a little before. Students must be at least 16 years of age, and we have to do PSEO paperwork to get you enrolled.

Since our first graduation in May 2008 (shout out here to the original 13!) over 500 local young people have now graduated from our school. üôÇ

Congratulations to our recent 2020 graduates! Small parking-lot ceremonies were held on May 21st, June 4th, and June 20th.

The following pictures will be in this week's Mesabi Daily News and Hibbing Daily Tribune, and another set will also be shared in the Hometown Focus.

Please forward and share with anyone who doesn't know what we're about! It's pretty simple... we're about our students! üôÇ

Thanks, Hendi

post_text:
Attn: ERATS families
Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.
Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org

post_text:
Summer School (2020)

If you are interested in Summer School at ERATS this summer, please contact Andy Bellefy (abellefy@mnerats.org) or Luke Carlson (lcarlson@mnerats.org) for information regarding Summer School.

If you can't reach us through our emails, contact the school at 218-744-7965.

Summer School Details:

- Starts June 1st and goes until June 25th
- Hours are (9:00 AM to 12:00 PM) Monday - Thursday
- Transportation available! Please let us know if your student needs assistance with any transportation needs to or from the school.
- Distance learning available for students
- Small groups (up to 10) is allowed in a classroom (mostly will be 1 on 1 with a staff member)

post_text:
Attention Seniors and Families!

This year we will be holding (3) separate, smaller outdoor "parking lot" graduation ceremonies. Each will be at the school where you will be able to receive your diploma while walking across a stage (in the front of the building under the canopy in case of rain).

üôÇ Because of the virus-rules, we won't be able to be inside the building together, but we will have caps, gowns, music, flowers, a slide-show, a staff video, presents, a professional photographer for you and family, and any other cool stuff we can think of.

It will be different than other years, but it will be good.

Days of the (3) mini-ceremonies:
Thursday, May 21st at 6:00 pm;
Thursday, June 4th at 6:00 pm; or
Saturday, June 20th at 6:00 pm.

You must be done with all credits at least 2 days before to participate in a ceremony. More information to follow soon ~ Hendi üôÇ

Good luck wherever you go in your future!

post_text: Lucas Jacka has been a wonderful part of the ERATS family the past 4 years. post_text: Hunter Hall has been a great addition to ERATS since he started with us 2 years ago. He is what you might call a gearhead; he loves to work on cars and go mudding in his free time (that's driving off-road for you non-gearheads). Congratulations Hunter!

post_text: This Monday, we say thank you to our last teacher, Dorothy Oie. Dorothy is our Ojibway language instructor, and she uses innovative, fun techniques to bring her passion to preserve the language to our students. Dorothy provides a calming presence; she has an abundance of patience and wisdom. Our students know that Dorothy is there for them, providing support and guidance in every capacity. Chi-Miigwech Dorothy for all that you do!

post_text: Alex Brusacoram has been a valued student at ERATS his entire high school career. He makes every class a joy to be a part of. In his free time he enjoys four-wheeling, fishing, gaming, reading, and coding. He's particularly interested in cars and electronics, and how they work. His favorite subject in school is science. He plans to first finish his ECM degree at Mesabi Range College (Eveleth), then go on to either work for SpaceX, Nasa, and/or go to school for Electrical Engineering (he's still figuring that out). ERATS wishes him luck, and we know he's going to do great things, no matter where he ends up.

post_text: Susan Moriarity has been a teacher at ERATS for 2 years, specializing in special education. She has been a fantastic and inspirational addition to the staff. She's the kind of rare teacher, the type students remember and talk about well into adulthood, who never gives up on a student, no matter how challenging their situation might be. These students discover new hope with someone like Ms. Moriarity. ERATS is lucky, and proud, to have her.

Survey link below :)

Schools are closed until March 27th to allow teachers to plan for longer-term distance learning.

By March 30th, the Minnesota Department of Education will give direction on if we will be returning to school buildings or starting state-wide K-12 distance learning.

During March 23rd - March 27th, our ERATS teachers will be working to develop equitable online and paper-pencil options for all students, while transportation staff and others will be delivering breakfasts and lunches to households in need.

Please complete the following short survey to help us in this process. Thanks so much! Amy Hendrickson 218-750-2980

post_text: East Range Academy took a trip to the Hegman Lake Pictographs, located on North Hegman Lake in the BWCA this Saturday and it was AMAZING! The rock art is considered the most photogenic pictograph within the State of MN, and some say it is a star chart, an almanac, and a timeline combined! Our students snowshoed the whole way there over the frozen lakes and enjoyed a perfect weather day for this once in a lifetime visitüåå

post_text: We will be doing a special field trip to see the Hegman Lake Pictographs on Feb 15! These pictographs are an amazing example of indigenous history and some say are a star chart, an almanac, and a timeline combined! We will be leaving the school at 11:30 and meeting the Outward Bound group for a short hike up South Hegman at 1:00 - 3:00. Dinner will be provided after the hike. Sign-up and permission slips will be available at the front desk starting on Monday! These pictographs are much more accessible in the Winter months, dont miss the opportunity to view this historical site!

post_text: There will be no classes this upcoming Monday and Tuesday, and we kick off the new semester when we return back on Wednesday. On Monday, in honor of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr, there will be a Field Trip to Duluth. We will be attending MLK events at Lake Street in Duluth, ending at the DECC. After the events, we will be going to lunch and to Adventure Zone. No money is needed. The van/bus will be leaving the school at 9:00 am and returning by 5:00 pm. Breakfast snacks will be provided. Permission slips have been available at the front desk and are required to participate. Happy Friday, have a great long weekend and see you all Semester 2!
